The '''[[2009 flu pandemic]]''' is a [[pandemic|global outbreak]] of a new strain of [[influenza A virus subtype H1N1]], first identified in April 2009, termed '''[[Pandemic H1N1/09 virus]]''' by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/Pandemic_h1n1_presstranscript_2009_07_07.pdf|title=Transcript of virtual press conference with Dr Keiji Fukuda, Assistant Director-General ad Interim for Health Security and Environment, World Health Organization|date=7 July 2009|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=26 October 2009}}</ref> and colloquially called '''swine flu'''. The outbreak was first observed in Mexico,<ref name=Mcneil20090427>{{cite news |title=Flu Outbreak Raises a Set of Questions |last=McNeil Jr. |first=Donald G. |date=26 April 2009 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=24 October 2009 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/27/health/27questions.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.oie.int/eng/press/en_090427.htm|title=A/H1N1 influenza like human illness in Mexico and the USA: OIE statement|author=Maria Zampaglione|publisher=[[World Organisation for Animal Health]]|date=29 April 2009|accessdate=29 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090430105521/http://www.oie.int/eng/press/en_090427.htm| archivedate= 30 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref> and quickly spread globally. On 11 June 2009, the WHO declared the outbreak to be a pandemic.<ref name=MargaretChanJune11>{{cite news|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2009/h1n1_pandemic_phase6_20090611/en/index.html|title=World now at the start of 2009 influenza pandemic|last=Chan|first=Dr. Margaret|date=11 June 2009|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=25 October 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091022123810/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2009/h1n1_pandemic_phase6_20090611/en/index.html| archivedate= 22 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UK National Institute for Medical Research WHO World Influenza Centre: Emergence and spread of a new influenza A (H1N1) virus, 12 June 09|url=http://www.nimr.mrc.ac.uk/wic/|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jhOOYh7N|archivedate=10 September 2009|deadurl=no|accessdate=2 September 2009}}</ref> The overwhelming majority of patients experience mild symptoms",<ref name=MargaretChanJune11/> but some persons are in higher risk groups, such as those with [[asthma]], [[diabetes]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flu.gov/individualfamily/healthconditions/diabetes/index.html|title=Diabetes and the Flu|publisher=U.S. Department of Health & Human Services|accessdate=25 October 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091025113447/http://www.flu.gov/individualfamily/healthconditions/diabetes/index.html| archivedate= 25 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/diabetes/news/docs/flu.htm|title=CDC's Diabetes Program – News & Information – H1N1 Flu|date=14 October 2009|work=CDC.gov|publisher=CDC|accessdate=25 October 2009|author=National Center for Chronic Disease Prevention and Health Promotion, Division of Diabetes Translation| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091023100843/http://www.cdc.gov/diabetes/news/docs/flu.htm| archivedate= 23 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> [[obesity]], [[heart disease]], or who are pregnant or have a weakened [[immune system]].<ref name=NYT5-27>{{cite news |last=Hartocollis |first=Anemona |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/28/health/policy/28flu.html |title='Underlying conditions' may add to flu worries |work=The New York Times |date=27 May 2009|accessdate=26 September 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090830210252/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/28/health/policy/28flu.html| archivedate= 30 August 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> In the rare severe cases, around 3–5 days after symptoms manifest, the sufferer's condition declines quickly, often to the point of [[respiratory failure]].<ref name=WHObriefingnoteOct16>{{cite news|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/h1n1_clinical_features_20091016/en/index.html|title=Clinical features of severe cases of pandemic influenza|date=16 October 2009|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=25 October 2009|location=Geneva, Switzerland| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091025105555/http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/h1n1_clinical_features_20091016/en/index.html| archivedate= 25 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

The virus reached the United Kingdom in April 2009.<ref name=Times6211122>{{cite news |url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/columnists/article6211122.ece |title=Swine flu by another name isn’t so catchy|work=The Sunday Times |location=UK |accessdate=4 May 2009|date=3 May 2009 |author=Dominic Rushe|quote=Sadly I don’t think this name change is going to stick. Flu epidemics used to get named after their country of origin. Mexico has so far been unbelievably lucky in its attempts to dodge this one. The Israelis tried to pass the name back last week – they don't like the swine appellation either. But they soon backed off after a furious Mexican response. Nobody worried about the effect on tourism or pig sales when the Spanish flu killed more than 50m people in 1918. | archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090508084854/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/columnists/article6211122.ece| archivedate= 8 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The first cases were confirmed on 27 April 2009 in passengers returning from Mexico. The first case of person to person transmission within the UK was announced on 1 May 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=First case of onward human to human swine flu transmission in England confirmed|author=HPA|url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1241180239108?p=1231252394302|accessdate=3 May 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090504060722/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1241180239108?p=1231252394302| archivedate= 4 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref> In the UK, 5- to 14-year-olds are the age group predominantly affected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1247125491112|title=Weekly pandemic flu update|date=9 July 2009|author=Health Protection Agency| accessdate= 16 September 2009 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Laboratory tests have demonstrated that older people have some immunity.<ref name=CIDRAP/>

After a slow start, the virus spread rapidly in the UK in July 2009, with new cases peaking at 110,000 in the last week of that month, according to The Health Protection Agency's modelling estimate, but declining sharply in the first week of August 2009.<ref name=HPAinfo/><ref name=BBC-BigDrop>{{cite news|title=Big drop in new swine flu cases |author=BBC|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8188027.stm|accessdate=6 August 2009 |date=6 August 2009 |work=BBC News }}</ref> Cases fell progressively down to 3,000 in the first week of September 2009, then began to rise again.<ref name=HPAinfo/> The decline in cases during the summer had been predicted, but a large surge was expected in the autumn to coincide with the normal flu season.<ref name=BBC-BigDrop/> Cases rose to 84,000 by the end of October, well below the summer's peak and then declined during November.<ref name=HPAinfo/>

