|-
|13 June
|Over 1,000 cases of swine flu confirmed in the UK.<ref name=HPAinfo/>
|-
|14 June
|First death, of patient with underlying health problems, reported at the [[Royal Alexandra Hospital (Paisley)|Royal Alexandra Hospital]] in [[Paisley]], Glasgow, Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8099832.stm |title=First UK swine flu patient death |publisher=BBC News  |date=15 June 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090627044921/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8099832.stm| archivedate= 27 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
|-
|26 June
|Second death, of patient with underlying health problems, of a six-year-old girl at [[Birmingham Children's Hospital]] in the [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands region]]. Her death was reported on 29 June.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/west_midlands/8124781.stm|title=Girl, nine, dies from swine flu|date=29 June 2009|publisher=BBC News  |accessdate=29 June 2009}}</ref>
|-
|30 June
|6,000 cases of swine flu confirmed in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |title=Update on swine flu cases |date=29 June 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1246260039528?p=1231252394302| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091121013624/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1246260039528?p=1231252394302| archivedate= 21 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref>
|-
|2 July
|The HPA announced that the containment approach to reduce spread was no longer appropriate given the clusters of cases around the UK, and would be replaced by a treatment phase in which everybody presenting symptoms would be treated if necessary without laboratory confirmation, but contacts would not be traced. Daily reports of confirmed cases are no longer being published.<ref name=HPAtreatmentApproach/>
|-
|6 July
|Three deaths in the UK bringing the total to seven. The new victims include two 9-year-old girls. NHS stated all three had "serious underlying health problems". The victims are from South London and Dewsbury in West Yorkshire.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/8137115.stm|title=Three more swine flu victims die |publisher=BBC |date=6 July 2009|accessdate=6 July 2009}}</ref>
|-
|9 July
|The government announced that there are now over 9,000 cases of Swine flu in the UK and 14 patients have died,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8142833.stm|title=UK swine flu death toll hits 14|publisher=BBC |date=9 July 2009|accessdate=9 July 2009}}</ref> 2 in Scotland, 5 in London, and the remainder elsewhere in England.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.london.nhs.uk/news-and-health-issues/press-releases/2009-press-releases/deaths-of-patients-with-swine-flu|title=Deaths of patients with swine flu|publisher=NHS|date=9 July 2009|accessdate=9 July 2009}}</ref>
|-
|10 July
|A 15th person has died from swine flu in Essex. Unlike previous cases, they had no underlying health conditions.<ref>[http://www.reuters.com/article/GCA-SwineFlu/idUSTRE5685ER20090710 UK records first H1N1 death in healthy patient, Reuters]</ref>
|-
|13 July
|2 more people die with swine flu in England.<ref>{{cite news |title=Girl's death takes flu toll to 16 |date=13 July 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8147759.stm |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref> One, a 6-year-old girl, who died of septacemia, and a middle-aged doctor. Initial reports that he died of Pulmonary Embolism were disproved on his final Post Mortem, which concluded that Swine Flu was a contributing factor in his death.<ref>{{cite news |title=Teenage girl with swine flu dies |date=21 July 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8161680.stm |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref>
|-
|16 July
|It emerges that 12 more people have died. The total now stands at 29. 85,000 people are estimated to be affected by swine flu as of 16 July, with 55,000 new infections in the preceding week according to HPA modelling.<ref>[http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/uk/pandemic%20threat%20worse%20than%20terror/3269392 Channel 4 News: UK's swine flu death toll is now 29]</ref>
|-
|23 July
|The National Pandemic Flu Service goes live in England for the first time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Flu infects 100,000 in past week |last=Triggle |first=Nick |date=23 July 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8163930.stm |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref> Shortly after it goes live, the Service gets over 2,000 hits per second. Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland can opt in for the service if the rate of infection increases.
|-
|21 August
| The first swine flu related death in Wales has been confirmed after a 55-year-old woman died.<ref>[http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2009/08/21/woman-55-confirmed-as-first-swine-flu-death-in-wales-91466-24499768/ WalesOnline – News – Wales News – Woman, 55, confirmed as first swine flu death in Wales<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
|-
|15 October
|Its announced that there were 27,000 new swine flu cases in the past week, up from 18,000 the week before, and new cases were rising more slowly than expected, but the number requiring treatment in intensive care had increased from 47 out of 290 hospitalised last week to 74 out of 364 hospitalised this week. The number of deaths in the UK rose to 106.<ref>{{cite news |title=Swine flu vaccine programme begins as deaths pass 100 mark |author=Jeremy Laurance, Health Editor |date=16 October 2009 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/swine-flu-vaccine-programme-begins-as-deaths-pass-100-mark-1803636.html | location=London| accessdate= 18 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091017081159/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/swine-flu-vaccine-programme-begins-as-deaths-pass-100-mark-1803636.html| archivedate= 17 October 2009| deadurl= no}}</ref>
|-
|21 October
|[[2009 flu pandemic vaccine|Swine Flu Vaccine]] became available across the UK and mass immunisation programme gets under way.<ref name=Telegraph20091021>{{cite news
|title=Swine flu: mass immunisation programme under way
|date=21 October 2009
|newspaper=The Telegraph
|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6393836/Swine-flu-mass-immunisation-programme-under-way.html
 | location=London | accessdate=29 March 2010}}</ref>
|-
|22 October
| It's announced that Swine flu cases in the UK almost doubled from the previous week to 53,000. The number of patients needing hospital care has risen to 506 in England with 99 in critical care – the highest since the pandemic began. Deaths increased to 128. The total number of cases is now estimated to be 435,000.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1222281/Swine-flu-cases-double-UK-week-death-toll-reaches-122.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Four die of swine flu in 24 hours and cases double in a week | first=Jenny | last=Hope | date=23 October 2009| accessdate= 23 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Swine flu doctors ’unnerved’ by patients’ decline |last=Smith |first=Rebecca |date=22 October 2009 |newspaper=The Telegraph |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6409329/Swine-flu-doctors-unnerved-by-patients-decline.html | location=London| accessdate= 23 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091025051556/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6409329/Swine-flu-doctors-unnerved-by-patients-decline.html| archivedate= 25 October 2009| deadurl= no}}</ref>
|-
|29 October
| Swine Flu cases rose by almost 50% to 78,000 new cases. Deaths increased to 137. Hospitalised patients increased to 751, of which 157 are in intensive care including nine people on [[ECMO]] (extracorporeal membrane oxygenation) machines. It is now estimated that there have been 521,000 cases in England since the pandemic began. It is also reported that one in three deaths are not in the "priority vaccination group" as currently defined by the government.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6461871/Swine-flu-One-in-three-deaths-not-in-priority-vaccination-group.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Swine flu: One in three deaths 'not in priority vaccination group' | first=Kate | last=Devlin | date=29 October 2009| accessdate= 29 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091103075830/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6461871/Swine-flu-One-in-three-deaths-not-in-priority-vaccination-group.html| archivedate= 3 November 2009| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-1223874/New-cases-swine-flu-jump-50-amid-increase-intensive-care-treatment.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=New cases of swine flu jump 50%, with children under four the hardest hit | first=Jenny | last=Hope | date=30 October 2009| accessdate= 29 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>
|-
|5 November
| New Swine Flu cases increased to 84,000. Deaths increased to 154. 848 people are hospitalised, 172 of which are in intensive care. It is thought that the rise in new cases was smaller this week due to school children being on their "half term" holidays. [[Andrew Lansley]], the [[Shadow Health Secretary]], called on the Government to commit to vaccinating all schoolchildren in the country, as well as university students.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/6509813/Swine-flu-schoolchildren-could-receive-vaccine.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Swine flu: schoolchildren 'could receive vaccine' | first=Kate | last=Devlin | date=5 November 2009| accessdate= 6 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091108173422/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/6509813/Swine-flu-schoolchildren-could-receive-vaccine.html| archivedate= 8 November 2009| deadurl= no}}</ref>
|-
|12 November
| The number of new swine flu cases in the past week fell by nearly a quarter to 64,000 in England. Deaths increased to 182 (124 deaths in England, 33 in Scotland, 11 in Northern Ireland and 14 in Wales).<ref name=express1>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/141238/Healthy-children-to-receive-flu-jab |title=Daily Express &#124; UK News :: Under-fives will have swine flu jab |publisher=Express.co.uk |accessdate=19 November 2009}}</ref> Hospitalised patients fell to 785, of whom 173 are in intensive care. The [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer]], [[Liam Donaldson|Sir Liam Donaldson]], said that the drop in new cases could be due to school children's half term break, the impact of which could last two weeks and that next week's figures should give a clearer picture of how the virus is developing. Shadow health secretary Andrew Lansley said the latest figures again illustrated the importance of vaccinating children. "This is further evidence that we need to begin planning a school and college-based vaccination programme immediately."<ref name=newdeaths>{{cite news |title=Swine flu cases drop in England |date=12 November 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8357279.stm |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6555080/Swine-flu-drop-in-cases-raises-hopes-for-peak-in-second-wave.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Swine flu: drop in cases raises hopes for peak in second wave | first=Kate | last=Devlin | date=12 November 2009| accessdate= 13 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091115102542/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6555080/Swine-flu-drop-in-cases-raises-hopes-for-peak-in-second-wave.html| archivedate= 15 November 2009| deadurl= no}}</ref>
|-
|19 November
| New Swine Flu cases decreased again from the previous week, down to 53,000 new cases in England in the last week. 783 patients were hospitalised. The number of deaths related to swine flu in the UK increased to 214<ref name=Telegraph20091119>{{cite news|title=Millions of healthy children to be given swine flu jab |last=Smith |first=Rebecca |date=19 November 2009 |newspaper=The Telegraph |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6607867/Millions-of-healthy-children-to-be-given-swine-flu-jab.html | location=London| accessdate= 19 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091122171657/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6607867/Millions-of-healthy-children-to-be-given-swine-flu-jab.html| archivedate= 22 November 2009| deadurl= no}}</ref> (142 in England). The HPA estimates that there have now been a total of 715,000 cases of swine flu since the pandemic began.<ref name=HPA20091119>{{cite web|title=Weekly pandemic flu media update |date=19 November 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=19 November 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1258560526320?p=1231252394302| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091121015303/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1258560526320?p=1231252394302| archivedate= 21 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publichealth/Flu/Swineflu/DH_108846 |title=19 November 2009 – Weekly swine flu update : Department of Health – Public health |publisher=Dh.gov.uk |accessdate=19 November 2009}}{{Dead link|date=June 2010}}</ref> The government has announced that all children under the age of five are to get the swine flu vaccine. Chief Medical Officer Sir Liam Donaldson said there had been a rise in serious illnesses recently among young children that was "causing concern". "We consider them to be seriously at risk". Latest figures showed that 81% of under-5s hospitalised with swine flu had no underlying health issues. The Conservative Party says that all under-25s should get the vaccine next.<ref name=express1/><ref name=BBC20091119>{{cite news|title=Under-fives to get swine flu jab |last=Triggle |first=Nick |date=19 November 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8368344.stm |accessdate=1 January 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091122115540/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8368344.stm| archivedate= 22 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
|-
|20 November
| The first officially confirmed cases of person-to-person transmission of a [[Tamiflu]]-resistant strain of swine flu in the world are reported to have happened between 5 patients at the [[University Hospital of Wales]] in [[Cardiff]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Walsh |first=Fergus |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8370859.stm |title=Tamiflu-resistant swine flu spreads 'between patients' |publisher=BBC News  |date=20 November 2009 |accessdate=27 November 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091126040533/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8370859.stm| archivedate= 26 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
|-
|26 November
| The number of new swine flu cases continue to fall, with 46,000 new cases in the last week, 7,000 less than the week before. However Swine flu deaths in England in a single week reached their highest level with a record 21 deaths, bringing the total deaths to 245 in the UK (163 in England). There were 753 hospitalised patients, 154 of those being in intensive care. The Government estimates more than a million people have now been vaccinated, roughly a month after the vaccination program started (that figure excludes health care workers, who are also being offered the vaccine). That means only about 1 in 10 of the 11 million people in the "at risk" priority groups have so far been vaccinated. Professor [[David Salisbury]], head of [[immunisation]] at the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] was disappointed, saying "Clearly I would have liked a bigger number...I would like to see an acceleration now".<ref>{{cite news|last=Triggle |first=Nick |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8381509.stm |title=Doctors 'need to speed up swine flu vaccinations' |publisher=BBC News  |date=26 November 2009 |accessdate=27 November 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091129043914/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8381509.stm| archivedate= 29 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6663972/Swine-flu-deaths-in-England-reach-highest-level.html |title=Swine flu deaths in England reach highest level |publisher=Telegraph |date=25 April 2009 |accessdate=27 November 2009 | location=London | first=Richard | last=Alleyne| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091128111412/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6663972/Swine-flu-deaths-in-England-reach-highest-level.html| archivedate= 28 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
|-
|3 December
| New Swine Flu cases more than halved from the previous week, dropping to 22,000 new cases in England in the last week. Total deaths increased to 270 (178 deaths in England). There are 747 hospitalised patients – 161 of which are in critical care. A further 600,000 people were vaccinated in the last week, bringing total to 1.6&nbsp;million people. In addition to that, 275,000 healthcare workers have been vaccinated out of nearly 2 million. [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer]] Sir Liam Donaldson said it was still "too early" to know whether the downward trend in new cases would continue and that his biggest worry was the virus mutating or mixing with other viruses and creating a new, more dangerous virus. Prof David Salisbury, head of immunisation at the Department of Health, said the vaccines with [[Immunologic adjuvant|adjuvants]], substances which boost the immune system and allow less active ingredient to be used in each dose, offer good protection even if the virus does change; "One of the advantages with adjuvanted vaccines is their ability to protect against drifted (mutated) strains. It opens the door for a whole new strategy in dealing with flu." The [[GlaxoSmithKline]] vaccine, [[Pandemrix]], which forms the bulk of the governments mass vaccination programme with 11.2&nbsp;million doses delivered so far to health services, contains an adjuvant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1259152076662?p=1231252394302 |title=Weekly pandemic flu media update |publisher=HPA |accessdate=4 December 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091203223838/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1259152076662?p=1231252394302| archivedate= 3 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8393651.stm |title=New infections of swine flu 'on the way down' |publisher=BBC News  |accessdate=4 December 2009 | date=3 December 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091206234705/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8393651.stm| archivedate= 6 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6719861/Change-in-swine-flu-virus-is-my-biggest-fear-Liam-Donaldson.html |title=Change in swine flu virus is my biggest fear: Liam Donaldson |publisher=Telegraph |date=25 April 2009 |accessdate=4 December 2009 | location=London | first=Rebecca | last=Smith| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091206031729/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6719861/Change-in-swine-flu-virus-is-my-biggest-fear-Liam-Donaldson.html| archivedate= 6 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publichealth/Flu/Swineflu/DH_109578 |title=3 December 2009 – Weekly swine flu update : Department of Health – Public health |publisher=Dh.gov.uk |accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref>
|-
|10 December
| New Swine Flu cases halved from the previous week, to 11,000 new cases in England. Deaths increased to 283 (191 in England) and there were currently 636 hospitalised patients. The number of people vaccinated increased to 2.3&nbsp;million. The estimated total number of cases is 795,000. The Chief Medical Officer Sir Liam Donaldson revealed that the swine flu pandemic is "considerably less lethal" than feared. An analysis of deaths to 8 November showed that 26 people have died for every 100,000 cases in England, meaning a [[death rate]] of 0.026% in those infected with Swine Flu. The highest death rate was in those aged over 65, and lowest in those aged 5 to 14. The average age at death was 39. Of the patients who died, 67% were in the "high risk" vaccination priority group and were eligible to get vaccinated, 36% had either no or only mild pre-existing illnesses. Sir Liam again urged people to come forward for immunisation, commenting that a lower impact than previously feared "is not a justification for public health inaction. Our data supports the priority vaccination of high risk groups. Given that a substantial minority of deaths occur in previously healthy people, there is a case for extending the vaccination programme".<ref>{{cite news|last=Triggle |first=Nick |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8406723.stm |title=Swine flu less lethal than feared |publisher=BBC News  |date=10 December 2009 |accessdate=15 January 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091216231059/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8406723.stm| archivedate= 16 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6780116/Swine-flu--considerably-less-lethal-than-feared.html |title=Swine flu: "considerably less lethal" than feared |publisher=Telegraph |date=10 December 2009 |accessdate=15 January 2010 | location=London | first=Kate | last=Devlin| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091213175240/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6780116/Swine-flu--considerably-less-lethal-than-feared.html| archivedate= 13 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publichealth/Flu/Swineflu/DH_109929 |title=10 December 2009 – Weekly swine flu update : Department of Health – Public health |publisher=Dh.gov.uk |date=10 December 2009 |accessdate=15 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1259152211290?p=1231252394302 |title=Weekly pandemic flu media update |publisher=HPA |accessdate=15 January 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100115023821/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1259152211290?p=1231252394302| archivedate= 15 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref>
|-
|17 December
| New Swine Flu cases again fell with 9000 people infected in last week. Total deaths in the UK increased to 299 (203 in England). The number of currently hospitalised patients fell to 523 patients of which more than 100 were in intensive care. 3 million people out of the 9&nbsp;million in the 1st vaccination priority groups have now been vaccinated including 100,000 pregnant women. In addition to that, 343,000 front line health workers have also been vaccinated. It appears that the second wave of Swine Flu is coming to an end but experts warn cases could rise again in the future in a "third wave" of swine flu.<ref name=news.bbc.co.uk>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8418899.stm |title=Fall in swine flu cases continues |publisher=BBC News  |date=17 December 2009 |accessdate=15 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6834606/Natural-swine-flu-defence-found.html |title=Natural swine flu defence found |publisher=Telegraph |date=18 December 2009 |accessdate=15 January 2010 | location=London | first=Rebecca | last=Smith| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091221203035/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/6834606/Natural-swine-flu-defence-found.html| archivedate= 21 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thereporters/ferguswalsh/2009/12/swine_flu_cases_continue_to_fall.html |title=Fergus On Flu: Swine flu cases continue to fall |publisher=BBC  |date=17 December 2009 |accessdate=15 January 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100217213326/http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thereporters/ferguswalsh/2009/12/swine_flu_cases_continue_to_fall.html| archivedate= 17 February 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publichealth/Flu/Swineflu/DH_110348 |title=17 December 2009 – Weekly swine flu update : Department of Health – Public health |publisher=Dh.gov.uk |date=17 December 2009 |accessdate=15 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1259152318661?p=1231252394302 |title=Weekly pandemic flu media update |publisher=HPA |accessdate=15 January 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100113213238/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1259152318661?p=1231252394302| archivedate= 13 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref>
|-
|24 December
| New cases of Swine Flu fell by a third to 6,000 cases this week. The total death figures will be updated by the HPA on Thursday 7 January. The number of hospitalised patients declined to 454 currently in hospital (as of 8&nbsp;am on 23 December).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1259152420791?p=1231252394302 |title=Weekly pandemic flu media update |publisher=HPA |accessdate=15 January 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100113214602/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1259152420791?p=1231252394302| archivedate= 13 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref>
|-
|31 December
| The HPA did not release estimate numbers this week, instead saying that flu activity is continuing to decrease across the UK but some caution must be exercised as this may be influenced by the holiday period. 496 patients were currently hospitalised in England as of 8&nbsp;am on 30 December (an increase from last week). A more detailed update will be released next week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1259152450217?p=1231252394302 |title=Weekly pandemic flu media update |publisher=HPA |accessdate=15 January 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100113215351/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1259152450217?p=1231252394302| archivedate= 13 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref>
|-
|8 January
| Swine Flu cases have continued to decrease, down to less than 5,000 new cases in the last week. Total UK deaths have increased to 360 (251 in England, 64 in Scotland, 28 in Wales and 17 in Northern Ireland). Currently hospitalised patients in England (as of 8&nbsp;am on 6 January) were 393, of which 103 were in critical care. So far, only 3.2&nbsp;million people have been vaccinated (out of 9 million in the priority groups), including 113,000 pregnant women (out of roughly 600,000), 86,000 under-5s (out of more than 3&nbsp;million) and an additional 373,000 front-line health workers (out of more than a million). The Head of Immunisation at the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]], Professor David Salisbury urged all those in the at-risk priority groups to get immunised, especially children under five and those with underlying health conditions, because while cases are currently down, it was not clear what would happen with swine flu over the year ahead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1262704890514?p=1259152466069 |title=Weekly pandemic flu media update |publisher=HPA |accessdate=15 January 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100113214353/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1262704890514?p=1259152466069| archivedate= 13 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Emma Wilkinson |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8448080.stm |title=Talks to offload swine flu vaccine under way |publisher=BBC News  |date=8 January 2010 |accessdate=15 January 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100114095147/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8448080.stm| archivedate= 14 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thereporters/ferguswalsh/ |title=Fergus On Flu |publisher=BBC  |accessdate=15 January 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100110192304/http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thereporters/ferguswalsh/| archivedate= 10 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
|}

==Reported cases==
{{Update|date=November 2009}}

Until 2 July 2009 the HPA published daily reports<ref name=HPAinfo/> of laboratory-confirmed cases with breakdown by region, by age, and by source of infection (travel, community, etc.). From that date routine laboratory testing of all suspected cases and reporting of figures was discontinued. {{As of|2009|7|8}} figures shown in this article are laboratory confirmed cases reported on 2 July.

Deaths are often reported as occurring "after contracting the swine flu virus" without flu being necessarily the cause of death of people with underlying health problems.

Researchers at Imperial College London said in July 2009 that the best estimate was that about 0.5% of those who get swine flu ''bad enough to seek medical help'' die from it, a figure very similar to the estimate for seasonal influenza.<ref>{{cite web |title=What are the chances of dying from swine flu? |date=17 July 2009 |accessdate=24 September 2009 |last=Walsh|first=Fergus|publisher=BBC  |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thereporters/ferguswalsh/2009/07/what_are_the_chances_of_dying_from_swine_flu.html}}</ref>

