===Detailed reports===
On 25 April 2009, a member of [[British Airways]] cabin crew was taken to [[Northwick Park Hospital]] in [[Harrow, London|Harrow]] and quarantined after falling ill with flu-like symptoms on a flight from Mexico City though he was later found not to have swine flu.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/apr/25/swine-flu-pandemic-mexico-flight|title=Cabin crew member in hospital after flight from swine flu-struck Mexico|work=Guardian |location=UK|accessdate=27 April 2009  | date=25 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090429082904/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/apr/25/swine-flu-pandemic-mexico-flight| archivedate= 29 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

On 26 April, two people were admitted to [[Monklands Hospital]] in [[Airdrie, North Lanarkshire|Airdrie]], [[North Lanarkshire]], with mild flu-like symptoms after returning from Mexico.<ref>{{cite news |date=26 April 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/8019544.stm |title=Scots tourists in swine flu alert |work=BBC News  |accessdate=26 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090427013219/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/8019544.stm| archivedate= 27 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name=northamptonshire1>{{cite news |date=26 April 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/northamptonshire/8019536.stm |title=Family alert to swine flu illness |work=BBC News  |accessdate=27 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090427013155/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/northamptonshire/8019536.stm| archivedate= 27 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The next day, the [[Cabinet Secretary for Health and Wellbeing]], [[Nicola Sturgeon]], confirmed that these were cases of the swine influenza A (H1N1) virus.<ref name=BBC_confirmed_cases>{{cite news |title=Scots swine flu cases confirmed |date=27 April 2009 |work=BBC News  |accessdate=27 April 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/glasgow_and_west/8020208.stm| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090430133018/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/glasgow_and_west/8020208.stm| archivedate= 30 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Authorities in both Scotland and England stated that there were no plans to trace the fellow airline passengers who may have travelled alongside the couple, since the authorities do not classify them as "close contacts".<ref>{{cite news |date=28 April 2009 |url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/display.var.2504776.0.passengers_wont_be_traced.php|title=Passengers 'won't be traced' |work=[[Glasgow Evening Times]] |accessdate=28 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090430065159/http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/display.var.2504776.0.passengers_wont_be_traced.php| archivedate= 30 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> These cases along with one in Spain are the first confirmed cases in Europe.<ref>{{cite web |title=Swine influenza – Health Protection Agency update |date=27 April 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1240812258582?p=1231252394302| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091121014633/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1240812258582?p=1231252394302| archivedate= 21 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref>

At noon on 29 April the government reported three more confirmed cases in the UK, including the first cases in England. All three had recently returned from Mexico.<ref name="Sky 3 more UK">{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/UK-News/Swine-Flu-Health-Chiefs-Urgently-Try-To-Increase-Stockpile-Of-Surgical-Masks-And-Sends-Out-Leaflet/Article/200904415271452?lpos=UK_News_Carousel_Region_0&lid=ARTICLE_15271452_Swine_Flu%3A_Health_Chiefs_Urgently_Try_To_Increase_Stockpile_Of_Surgical_Masks_And_Sends_Out_Leaflet_|title=Swine Flu: Girl Among Three New Cases In UK |date=29 April 2009|publisher=Sky News|accessdate=29 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090501160331/http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/UK-News/Swine-Flu-Health-Chiefs-Urgently-Try-To-Increase-Stockpile-Of-Surgical-Masks-And-Sends-Out-Leaflet/Article/200904415271452?lpos=UK_News_Carousel_Region_0&lid=ARTICLE_15271452_Swine_Flu%3A_Health_Chiefs_Urgently_Try_To_Increase_Stockpile_Of_Surgical_Masks_And_Sends_Out_Leaflet_| archivedate= 1 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The secondary school, Paignton Community and Sports College, closed for seven days.<ref name=Guardian3004>{{cite news|work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=30 April 2009|title=Emergency order: UK buys 60m masks as new cases emerge: Millions more doses of antiviral drugs requested and mass leafleting strategy unveiled in 'pandemic preparedness' plan|author=Owen Bowcott, Severin Carrell David Teather|page=4|quote=The decision to close the school in Devon until next Tuesday is in line with Health Protection Agency and WHO guidelines: seven days is the incubation period for the flu.}}</ref>

By 26 May the number of people who had contracted the disease in-country increased to 125, the highest in Europe and triple the second highest, Spain.<ref>[http://ecdc.europa.eu/en/files/pdf/Health_topics/Situation_Report_090526_1700hrs.pdf]{{Dead link|date=November 2009}}</ref>

On 28 May, sixty four people connected with a primary school in Birmingham were diagnosed with swine flu .<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/west_midlands/8072374.stm |title=School swine flu cases rise to 64 |publisher=BBC News  |date=28 May 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090601153355/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/west_midlands/8072374.stm| archivedate= 1 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

On 8 June the HPA issued a report stating that the majority of cases are in school age children and young adults,<ref name=HPA8Jun09>[http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAwebFile/HPAweb_C/1244442493055 Swine-lineage Influenza A H1N1 UK update 8 June 09]</ref> which has not been the case in most pandemics with the notable exception of [[1918 flu pandemic|1918]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Simonsen |first=L |coauthors=Clarke M, Schonberger L, Arden N, Cox N, Fukuda K |title=Pandemic versus epidemic influenza mortality: a pattern of changing age distribution |journal=J Infect Dis |volume=178 |issue=1 |pages=53–60 |year=1998 |month=July |pmid=9652423}}</ref>

On 25 June the chief medical officer Sir Liam Donaldson said certain areas were seeing rapid community spread which meant that it was no longer practical to attempt in those areas (initially parts of London, the west Midlands and east Berkshire<ref>{{cite web |title=Radical shift in antiviral use considered |last=Walsh |first=Fergus |date=27 June 2009 |accessdate=24 September 2009 |publisher=BBC  |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thereporters/ferguswalsh/2009/06/radical_shift_in_antiviral_use_considered.shtml}}</ref>) to put a ring around the outbreaks by tracing the people with whom confirmed cases have come into contact and giving them drugs to try to prevent flu developing. In these areas, anti-viral drugs may in the future only be given to people showing symptoms, and tracing of contacts will stop. The contingency plans always envisaged the containment phase would not last indefinitely.<ref name=CMO25Jun09>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8118755.stm Statement by Chief Medical Officer 25 June 2009]</ref> The start of the treatment (as against containment) approach was announced on 2 July 2009.<ref name=HPAtreatmentApproach>{{cite web |title=Treatment approach announced for pandemic flu |date=2 July 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/servlet/Satellite?c=HPAweb_C&cid=1246519368102&pagename=HPAweb%252FHPAwebStandard}}</ref>

Every year in late June and early July the [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] tennis championships are held in London, attracting worldwide interest and with many hours of UK television coverage every day. On 1 July 2009 it was reported that 28 Wimbledon staff had been asked to stay at home with flu-like symptoms. Two named players are reported to have caught the virus.<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1196669/Fears-Wimbledon-players-struck-swine-flu.html Mail Online: Two Wimbledon players struck down by swine flu, 1 July 2009]</ref>

A study published in the August 2009 issue of [[The Lancet]] (available on 20 July) suggests that prolonging the school holidays could reduce the spread of the virus by up to 17%. This would be disruptive, and would not reduce the overall number of infections, but could delay the spread and buy time for preparation of a vaccine. The government's advice is that schools should not be closed, but that the evidence will be reviewed in August as school summer holidays end.<ref>{{cite news |title=Swine flu: schools should close to halt spread of virus ministers told |last=Wardrop |first=Murray |date=21 July 2009 |newspaper=The Telegraph |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/5874683/Swine-flu-schools-should-close-to-halt-spread-of-virus-ministers-told.html | location=London| accessdate= 16 September 2009 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Call to close schools to curb flu |date=21 July 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8160314.stm |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref>

==Public information==
The Department of Health announced on 29 April 2009 that they intended to send an information leaflet on swine flu to every household in the UK. The information leaflets were distributed at the beginning of May.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8023977.stm |title=UK homes to get swine flu advice |work=BBC News  |date=29 April 2009|accessdate=29 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090430193704/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8023977.stm| archivedate= 30 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8033048.stm |title=Swine flu leaflet delivery begins |work=BBC News  |date=5 May 2009|accessdate=5 May 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090508104300/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8033048.stm| archivedate= 8 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> On 29 April, [[Alan Johnson]] announced that television and radio advice would also be broadcast starting on 30 April.<ref name=BBC2904>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8024690.stm|title=WHO raises pandemic alert level|date=29 April 2009|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=29 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090430163952/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8024690.stm| archivedate= 30 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> On 30 April 2009, a swine flu information line was launched with advice on setting up "flu friends" (this is not the National Flu Line service mentioned below).<ref name=BBC2904/>

The Department of Health Pandemic Plan (revised November 2007) states ''"UK health departments (directorate in Scotland) will run a national door drop and advertising campaign in [[Pandemic phase 5|Phase 5]], alerting the public to the heightened risk, emphasising the need for personal preparation and socially responsible behaviour. A public information film will demonstrate how to slow the spread of the virus, and the National Flu Line service will be available. Information materials will also be available through primary care, pharmacies and on the Department of Health website."''<ref name=PandemicPlan/> After criticism of the lateness of its launch, it was announced in late July that the National Flu Line service was to be launched on 24 July 2009.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.e-health-insider.com/news/4798/no_national_flu_line_until_autumn
|title=No National Flu Line until autumn
|publisher=E-Health Insider
|accessdate=30 April 2009
|date=29 April 2009
}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Burnham under fire on flu advice |date=20 July 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8158468.stm |quote=Health Secretary Andy Burnham is to outline plans for a swine flu advice service amid criticism over its delayed launch. |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref>

There are government websites with general information and the latest updates on human swine flu in England,<ref name=HPAinfo/> Northern Ireland,<ref name=NIinfo>[http://www.dhsspsni.gov.uk/ Northern Ireland Department of Health, Social Services and Public Safety news releases, including day-by-day updates on confirmed swine flu cases (''this link is unlikely to change'')] The daily updates give the current number of cases confirmed and under investigation, with additional details, and are linked from this page.<br />[http://www.northernireland.gov.uk/news/news-dhssps/news-dhssps-29062009-swine-flu-update.htm Northern Ireland Department of Health, Social Services and Public Safety update on confirmed swine flu cases: 29 June 2009 (''this link will be updated to reference the latest update'')]<!--The link to the latest press release should be updated as new update releases are issued--></ref> Scotland,<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/swineflu Latest Scottish Government swine flu news release]</ref><ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/By-Topic/Q/Topic/20 Scottish Government Health and Community Care News website]</ref> and Wales.<ref name=WalesInfo>[http://www.wales.nhs.uk/sites3/page.cfm?orgid=457&pid=38185 NHS Wales swine flu web page with links to daily updates]</ref>

The HPA website includes frequently updated advice for the public,<ref name=HPApublicadvice>{{cite web |title=Swine flu: advice for the public |date=28 September 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&Page&HPAwebAutoListName/Page/1240812233855?p=1240812233855}}</ref> advice on exclusion from schools and workplaces<ref name=HPAexclusions>[http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1241418706890 HPA: Advice on Exclusion from Schools and Workplaces. Last revision 7 May 09]</ref> (and a document specifically for schools),<ref name=HPAschools>{{cite web |title=HPA advice on actions to be taken in a school. 8 May 09 |archiveurl=http://www.hpa.org.uk/hpr/archives/2009/news1809.htm |archivedate=28 June 2009}}</ref> and information for health professionals.<ref name=HPAprofessionals>{{cite web |title=Pandemic (H1N1) 2009 Influenza: information for health professionals |date=30 September 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&Page&HPAwebAutoListName/Page/1240812234677?p=1240812234677}}</ref>

During the initial containment phase of the swine flue outbreak the HPA published detailed information in daily and weekly reports linked from its Epidemiological data page on its website.<ref name=HPAinfo/> On 2 July, when the policy of containment was dropped in favour of treatment of presumed cases, the daily updates of laboratory confirmed cases were stopped.<ref name=HPAchange>{{cite web |title=Update on swine flu cases |date=2 July 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1246519358678?p=1231252394302#skip| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091121013200/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1246519358678?p=1231252394302| archivedate= 21 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref> A weekly epidemiological update and pandemic flu update are published each Tuesday, with much detailed information including regional information and breakdown by age.

==Control measures==
{{Main|2009 swine flu outbreak#Prevention and treatment|l1=Prevention and treatment for the 2009 swine flu outbreak}}
On 11 May 2009 UK epidemiologists at [[Imperial College London]] considered that H1N1 swine flu was spreading fast enough to justify the preparations for a pandemic. It was showing "sustained human-to-human transmission", thereby justifying the WHO's pandemic phase 5 rating. It is estimated that on average each person who contracts flu passes it on to between 1.4 and 1.6 other people, no worse than the three [[influenza pandemic]]s of the twentieth century. Early analysis suggested that the spread was likely to be similar to the earlier pandemics. Up to the date of the study, clinical severity was similar to [[Asian Flu|1957]] and less than 1918 flu pandemic. However, the clinical severity of the outbreak and how the virus will evolve cannot yet be predicted.<ref>[http://www.newscientist.com/article/dn17109-first-analysis-of-swine-flu-spread-supports-pandemic-plan.html New Scientist magazine website: First analysis of swine flu spread supports pandemic plan, 11 May 09]</ref>

===Travel to and from affected areas===
{{Update|date=February 2010}}
On 27 April, the [[Foreign & Commonwealth Office]] advised against all but essential travel to Mexico<ref name="FCO travel info">[http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/travelling-and-living-overseas/travel-advice-by-country/north-central-america/mexico Mexico Travel Advice], ''[[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]'', 27 April 2009. Retrieved 28 April 2009.</ref> and stated that [[British nationality law|British citizens]] in Mexico... "may wish to consider whether they should remain in Mexico at this time". On 28 April the Mexican Tourist Board estimated that there were "a few thousand" British tourists in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.travelweekly.co.uk/Articles/2009/04/28/30841/swine-flu-forces-mexico-tourism-board-to-rethink-uk.html |title=Swine Flu forces Mexico Tourism Board to rethink UK campaign |work=[[Travel Weekly]] |date=28 April 2009 |accessdate=28 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090503125251/http://www.travelweekly.co.uk/Articles/2009/04/28/30841/swine-flu-forces-mexico-tourism-board-to-rethink-uk.html| archivedate= 3 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref>

Holiday companies [[Thomas Cook]] and Airtours said that between them they had about "3,000 holidaymakers in Mexico" as of 28 April 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/local-news/2009/04/28/swine-flu-cannot-be-contained-100252-23490407/ |title=Swine flu halts flights to Mexico |work=[[Liverpool Echo]] |date=28 April 2009 |accessdate=28 April 2009}}</ref> The first British tourists being brought back early from Mexico on 28 April 2009 told reporters that they had received little or no information about health precautions, either from the Mexican authorities, hotels, or from local tour guides.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.birminghammail.net/news/top-stories/2009/04/28/passengers-arriving-in-birmingham-from-mexico-today-claimed-they-had-been-kept-in-the-dark-over-the-swine-flu-crisis-97319-23490833/ |title=Passengers arriving in Birmingham from Mexico today claimed they had been kept in the dark over the swine flu crisis |work=[[Birmingham Evening Mail]] |date=28 April 2009|accessdate=28 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090503072618/http://www.birminghammail.net/news/top-stories/2009/04/28/passengers-arriving-in-birmingham-from-mexico-today-claimed-they-had-been-kept-in-the-dark-over-the-swine-flu-crisis-97319-23490833/| archivedate= 3 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

A leaflet is being distributed at all ports of entry into the UK providing passengers arriving in the UK with information on swine flu.<ref>[http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAwebFile/HPAweb_C/1240986139568 UK Border Agency leaflet: Advice for People Entering the UK with Influenza-type Symptoms]{{Dead link|date=November 2009}}</ref>

Until 21 May HPA staff met travellers arriving from Mexico. This was discontinued on 22 May, but advice remained that travellers from affected areas who become unwell within seven days of arrival, and contacts with symptoms of a confirmed or probable case, should stay at home and contact their GP or [[NHS Direct]]. Contact tracing of passengers deemed to be at risk of swine flu will be carried out on the basis of risk, as for other communicable diseases.<ref name=HPAinfo21may/>

===Preparations===
[[Image:Tamiflu.JPG|thumb|120px|Tamiflu, [[influenza]] [[anti-viral drug]]]]
Information, advice, and guidance both general and for specific cases (schools, workplaces) is being made available and updated by the HPA (see [[#Public information campaign|Public information campaign]] section above).

As of 13 June 2009 the government estimated that the UK has enough [[anti-viral drug]]s for 50% of the population but has plans to raise that figure to 80%.<ref>{{cite news |title='Unpredictable' swine flu spreads |date=13 June 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8098895.stm |quote=A further 117 patients in England and 55 in Scotland have been confirmed with swine flu, pushing the UK total to 1,164. |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref>

There is a pandemic plan covering topics from distributing the drugs and setting up helplines to closing schools and banning public events which was tested in a large exercise in 2007.<ref name=PandemicPlan>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publicationsandstatistics/Publications/PublicationsPolicyAndGuidance/DH_080734
|title=Pandemic flu: A national framework for responding to an influenza pandemic
|publisher=UK Department of Health
|accessdate=30 April 2009
|date=November 2007}}
</ref><ref name=IndepFaceMask/> There is also a specific response plan for London.<ref>[http://www.londonprepared.gov.uk/downloads/londonsplans/london-flu-planV4.pdf London Regional Resilience Flu Pandemic Response Plan: Special Arrangements for Dealing with Pandemic Influenza in London], version 4, March 2009</ref> [[Oseltamivir]] (Tamiflu) and [[zanamivir]] (Relenza), the two anti-virals known to be effective, must be taken within 48 hours of onset of symptoms or earlier to be effective;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.druglib.com/druginfo/tamiflu/indications_dosage/ |title=Tamiflu (Oseltamivir) – Indications and Dosage |publisher=Druglib.com |date=4 February 2008 |accessdate=29 April 2009}}</ref> the positive effects are greatest if treatment is started within six hours.<ref>[http://www.sosindonesia.com/library/Important%20Tips%20for%20Fighting%20The%20Avian%20Influenza.pdf Important Tips for Fighting The Avian Influenza]</ref>

The HPA reported in its 24 June 2009 weekly epidemiological report that all 17 samples of the virus laboratory tested for resistance that week were found to be [[drug resistance|sensitive]] to oseltamivir and zanamivir, but resistant to [[amantadine]].<ref name=HPAweekly24Jun09>{{cite web |title=Weekly epidemiological update |date=22 October 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAweb&Page&HPAwebAutoListName/Page/1243928258560| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091120041738/http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAweb&Page&HPAwebAutoListName/Page/1243928258560| archivedate= 20 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref> The first case of resistance of the virus to oseltamivir, in Denmark, was reported on 29 June 2009.<ref>{{cite web |title=Swine Flu Sample Resistant to Antiviral Oseltamivir |date=30 June 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/servlet/Satellite?c=HPAweb_C&cid=1246345135429&pagename=HPAweb%252FHPAwebStandard}}</ref>

On 5 May 2009 plans were announced for pupils unable to sit examinations at schools affected by flu to be assessed in other ways to ensure that children are not disadvantaged.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exam plans if swine flu spreads |date=5 May 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/8033668.stm |quote=Secondary pupils taking exams this summer whose schools are disrupted by swine flu will be able to get 'special consideration'. |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref>

The Department of Health has listed all the pandemic flu guidance that it had published as of 8 June 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Department of Health flu guidance publications as of 8 June 2009|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publichealth/Flu/PandemicFlu/DH_093202|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jhOPSEf5|archivedate=10 September 2009|accessdate=2 September 2009}}</ref>

===Testing suspected cases===
====Genetic analysis====
Samples from suspected cases have been analysed by the [[National Institute for Medical Research]] in London, which is also examining samples of the U.S. strain of the disease.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nimr.mrc.ac.uk/news/2009/h1n1_02may09/ |title=NIMR scientists discuss swine-like human influenza A H1N1 |publisher=National Institute for Medical Research|date=1 May 2009 |accessdate=5 May 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090617021308/http://www.nimr.mrc.ac.uk/news/2009/h1n1_02may09/| archivedate= 17 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

By 8 May 2009 the US [[Centres for Disease Control and Prevention]] had made genetic information on the swine flu virus available, and the virus from European samples had been isolated and its full genetic fingerprint determined by UK researchers.<ref name=BBCsequencing>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8040000.stm BBC: UK swine flu genetics unravelled. 8 May 09]</ref> The genetics and effects of the virus in general are discussed in the article on the [[2009 swine flu outbreak#Genetics and effects|2009 swine flu outbreak]].

====Diagnosis====
The fastest way for laboratory confirmation of swine flu is by the [[Polymerase chain reaction|PCR]] method, described as a real-time method. According to the World Health Organization there are four laboratories in the UK able to perform PCR to diagnose influenza A (H1N1) virus infection in humans: Regional Virus Laboratory, [[Royal Victoria Hospital, Belfast]], NI; Regional Virus Laboratory, [[Gartnavel General Hospital]], Glasgow, Scotland; Health Protection Agency, [[UK statutory notification system|Centre for Infections, Enteric, Respiratory, & Neurological Virus Laboratory]], London; [[National Influenza Centers|WHO Collaborating Centre for Reference and Research on Influenza]], National Institute for Medical Research, London.<ref>[http://www.who.int/csr/resources/publications/swineflu/InfluenzaLabsWithPCRcapacityToDetectInfluenzaA_20090508a.pdf WHO list of countries able to perform PCR to diagnose influenza A (H1N1) virus infection in humans, 8 May 09]</ref>

Another laboratory confirmation is a fourfold increase in virus-specific antibodies 10 to 14 days later.<ref>[http://www.selectscience.net/product-news/sterilin-limited/sterilin-backs-hpa-guidelines-for-swine-flu-detection/?artID=18071 Article describing HPA guidelines for detecting swine flu]</ref>

From 2 July 2009 when a treatment, rather than containment, approach was adopted, the official clinical diagnostic criteria became: "fever ([[pyrexia]] ≥38 °C) or a history of fever, '''and''' also influenza-like illness (two or more of the following symptoms: cough; sore throat; [[rhinorrhoea]]; limb or joint pain; headache; vomiting or [[diarrhoea]]) '''or''' severe and/or life-threatening illness suggestive of an infectious process".<ref name=HPA4medics>{{cite web |title=Pandemic (H1N1) 2009 Influenza: information for health professionals |date=30 September 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/servlet/Satellite?c=Page&childpagename=HPAweb%252FPage%252FHPAwebAutoListName&cid=1240812234677&p=1240812234677&pagename=HPAwebWrapper}}</ref>

;"Laboratory confirmed" cases
Professor Neil Ferguson, an epidemiologist at Imperial College London, who advises the Government and the World Health Organisation, said on 8 June 2009 that HPA statistics were at best accounting for half of cases.<ref>[http://www.esnews.co.uk/?p=3938&mode=1 Emergency Services news: Number of UK swine flu cases underestimated, 8 June 2009]</ref>

In the [[2009 flu pandemic in the United States|USA]] mathematical modelling based on surveys estimated that there were about 1 million cases of H1N1 flu on 25 June 2009, compared to 28,000 reported officially.<ref>[http://www.forbes.com/feeds/hscout/2009/06/25/hscout628467.html Forbes – 1&nbsp;million Americans Likely Stricken by Swine Flu: CDC]{{Dead link|date=June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Areas Hit Hard by Flu in Spring See Little Now |author=Anemona Hartocollis and Donald G. McNeil Jr.|date=8 October 2009 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=24 October 2009 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/08/health/08flu.html| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091023110728/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/08/health/08flu.html| archivedate= 23 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Such a study has not been carried out in the UK.

As of 2 July 2009 GPs will diagnose based on clinical observation and routine swabbing will stop,<ref>{{cite web |title=Treatment approach announced for pandemic flu |date=2 July 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1246519368102}}</ref> and the HPA will "no longer be providing a daily update of the numbers of cases confirmed through laboratory tests"<ref>{{cite web |title=Changes to HPA pandemic flu media updates |date=3 July 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1246607819501?p=1231252394302| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091121013018/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1246607819501?p=1231252394302| archivedate= 21 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref>

===Hygiene recommendations===
According to the Health Protection Agency's "Swine flu: frequently asked questions" web page,<ref name=HPAswineflufaq>{{cite web |title=Swine flu: frequently asked questions |date=10 December 2009 |publisher=Health Protection Agency |accessdate=15 December 2009 |url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1240812255916?p=1244763941666| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091214075812/http://www.hpa.org.uk/webw/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1240812255916?p=1244763941666| archivedate= 14 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref> transmission of this new virus is thought to occur in the same way as seasonal flu:
* large droplets from coughing and/or sneezing by an infected person within a short distance (usually 1 metre or less) of someone;
* touching or shaking the hand of an infected person, and then touching your eyes, nose or mouth without first washing your hands;
* touching surfaces or objects (e.g. door handles) that have become contaminated with the flu virus, and then touching your eyes, nose or mouth without first washing your hands.

When the issue of touching your eyes, nose or mouth is combined with other [[infection control]] practices and good hygiene measures as recommended by the Health Protection Agency's website,<ref name=HPAinfo/> the following recommendations emerge as important ways to help reduce the spread of swine flu and other viruses:
* Don't touch your eyes, nose or mouth without first washing your hands.
* Cover your nose and mouth when coughing or sneezing, and use a tissue when possible.
* Dispose of dirty tissues promptly and carefully.
* Maintain good basic hygiene, for example [[hand washing|washing hands]] frequently with soap and water to reduce the spread of the virus from your hands to your face, or to other people.
* Clean hard surfaces, such as door handles, frequently using a normal cleaning product.
* Make sure children follow this advice.
* Anyone with swine flu or being investigated as a possible case will be given anti-virals and asked to stay at home and limit their contact with other people.
* Where anti-virals are prescribed the course of treatment must be followed and completed, although it may sometimes cause nausea.

For people belonging to a high-risk group it is particularly important that they start taking anti-virals as soon as possible after infection. High-risk groups include people with long-term conditions, those over 65, children under five and pregnant women.<ref name=HPA4medics/>

===Immunity===
A study at the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] published in May 2009 found that children had no pre-existing [[immunity (medical)|immunity]] to the new strain but that adults, particularly those over 60, had some degree of immunity. Children showed no cross-reactive [[antibody]] reaction to the new strain, adults aged 18 to 64 had 6–9%, and older adults 33%.<ref name=CIDRAP>[http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/cidrap/content/influenza/swineflu/news/may2109serum-jw.html CIDRAP news: Some immunity to novel H1N1 flu found in seniors, 21 May 2009]</ref> The large proportion of cases in the UK affecting children and young adults is consistent with this pattern of resistance.<ref name=Young>[http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAwebFile/HPAweb_C/1243322117077 HPA Update 26 May 09]</ref><ref name=Young2>[http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAwebFile/HPAweb_C/1245581553306 HPA epidemiological update for 24 June 09]</ref>

===Vaccine===
{{Main|2009 flu pandemic vaccine}}
The usual [[flu season|seasonal flu]] [[vaccine]]s give little or no immunity against the new strain of flu. There is an international program to produce a vaccine which will be effective against the new H1N1 strain. The chief medical officer Sir Liam Donaldson said on 25 June that it seemed likely that the UK would receive the first batches of vaccines slightly earlier than expected, possibly from August rather than the autumn as first expected, although some industry sources do not expect supplies to be available so soon. The government has contracts for 132 million doses.<ref name=CMO25Jun09/> There are risks involved in shifting resources to the new vaccine: it will not be possible to produce the seasonal flu vaccine, and it is possible that the virus will [[mutation|mutate]] to make a vaccine developed before the mutation ineffective.

===Possible use of face-masks===
[[Image:Alan Johnson -9Oct2007-2.jpg|thumb|120px|Alan Johnson, Health Secretary at the time of the outbreak]]
The then [[Secretary of State for Health|Health Secretary]] Alan Johnson told MPs on 27 April that "Although we are aware that face-masks are being given out to the public in Mexico, the available [[scientific evidence]] does not support the general wearing of face-masks by those who are not ill, whilst going about their normal activities."<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8021813.stm Swine flu cases confirmed in UK], BBC News Online, 27 April 2009</ref>

Professor Steve Field, chairman of the Royal College of General Practitioners, said people in the UK were "perfectly safe at the moment", and did not need to start wearing face-masks or stop eating pork.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK prepared for swine flu – Brown |date=28 April 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8021916.stm |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref>

The Head of Pandemic Planning at the [[Royal College of General Practitioners]], Dr Maureen Baker, stated on 27 April that "Masks become ineffective when they become damp or after a few hours. There has been a lot of debate on the use of face-masks and some authorities say that, in the community, the most effective use is to give to patients who may have symptoms when they present in the surgery – that should help reduce the infectivity of that patient to surgery staff and other patients. I expect the Department of Health will issue guidance on use of face-masks if we move into a pandemic phase."<ref>{{cite news |title=Swine flu: Your questions |date=1 May 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8020596.stm |quote=BBC News online put a number of your questions to the experts. |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref> Masks may not protect the wearer from inhalation of the virus, but might protect other people from picking up the virus from the wearer.<ref name=IndepFaceMask>[http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-wellbeing/health-news/will-a-face-mask-help-protect-me-are-there-enough-antiviral-drugs-1675173.html Will a face mask help to protect me? Are there enough anti-viral drugs?], ''The Independent'', 28 April 2009</ref>

Professor John Oxford, a virologist at leading London hospital, [[Barts and The London NHS Trust|The Barts and the London]], said: "Really, there is very little evidence that masks actually offer much protection against flu."<ref>{{cite news |title=Can masks help stop flu spread? |last=Triggle |first=Nick |date=29 April 2009 |newspaper=BBC News  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8024605.stm |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref>

It is reported that the UK government is urgently seeking to acquire more face-masks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/97522/Swine-flu-Why-face-masks-could-be-useless |title=Daily Express &#124; UK News :: Swine flu: Why face masks could be useless |publisher=Express.co.uk |accessdate=29 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090501055556/http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/97522/Swine-flu-Why-face-masks-could-be-useless| archivedate= 1 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name=dailymail1>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1174313/8216-I-8217-ve-experienced-like-8217--England-8217-s-victim-contract-swine-flu-human-speaks-ordeal.html |title=NHS under strain as doctors warn of lack of anti-viral drugs and shortage of facemasks &#124; Mail Online |work=Daily Mail |location=UK |accessdate=29 April 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Smith |first=Rebecca |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/5238448/Swine-flu-NHS-orders-30-million-extra-face-masks.html |title=Swine flu: NHS orders 30 million extra face masks |publisher=Telegraph |date=25 April 2009 |accessdate=29 April 2009 | location=London| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090501230513/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/swine-flu/5238448/Swine-flu-NHS-orders-30-million-extra-face-masks.html| archivedate= 1 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

The advice given by authorities in several countries on the use of face masks has been summarised in an article, with many references, published on 4 June 2009.<ref>[http://elements.healthspace.com/?p=950 Information from several Health Agencies about face masks.]</ref>

{{Quotation|Aside from their obligations under health and safety legislation, employers can help to minimise the spread of the virus and support good infection control practice by positively encouraging any employee who reports feeling unwell with influenza-like symptoms to stay at home until their symptoms resolve, by sending people home who develop influenza-like illness at work (avoiding public transport and wearing a face mask if possible) and by ensuring that stocks of surgical face-masks are available in the workplace for symptomatic staff to wear until they get home.|[[UK Department of Health|DoH]] Pandemic Flu Plan<ref name=PandemicPlan/>|November 2007}}

